Spring Security:
  Spring Security is a powerful framework used to handle:
    Authentication (Who are you?)
    Authorization (What can you access?)
    Protection against attacks (CSRF, XSS, session fixation, etc.)

  Points:
      Spring Security uses filter chain pattern
      JWT → stateless, stored in client
      SAML → SSO with IdP
      Always validate:
            Token expiry
            Signature
      JWT + Spring Security:
            Login API → generate token
            Every request → validate token
            No session storage
      SAML + Spring Security
            Configure IdP metadata
            Enable saml2Login()
            Works automatically with SSO
      AuthenticationManager → delegates
      AuthenticationProvider → validates
      JWT → stateless, scalable
      Session → stateful, server memory
      Stateless → no storage, scalable
      API Gateway + JWT → best for microservices
      OAuth2 → login via Google/Okta
      API Gateway → central security
      JWT → stateless → scalable
      Refresh Token → session replacement
      OAuth2 + JWT → hybrid modern approach
      Gateway validates token → services trust
                  
  Architecture Overview:
    1. Security Filter Chain
    Every request passes through a chain of filters.
    Example flow: Request → FilterChain → Authentication → Authorization → Controller
    Important filters: UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter, BearerTokenAuthenticationFilter (JWT) and SecurityContextPersistenceFilter

    2. Core Components
      🔹 Authentication - Represents user identity.
             Authentication auth = new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(username, password);
      🔹 AuthenticationManager - Responsible for validating credentials.
            authenticationManager.authenticate(auth);
      🔹 AuthenticationProvider - Actual logic for authentication (DB, LDAP, JWT, etc.)
      🔹 UserDetailsService -  Loads user from DB: UserDetails loadUserByUsername(String username);
      🔹 SecurityContext - Stores authenticated user info (ThreadLocal)

Basic Configuration (Spring Boot 3+):
@Bean
SecurityFilterChain securityFilterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
    http
        .csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable())
        .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
            .requestMatchers("/public/**").permitAll()
            .anyRequest().authenticated()
        )
        .formLogin();
    return http.build();
}

JWT Authentication (Stateless):
    JSON Web Token is a compact token used for stateless authentication.
    Structure: Header.Payload.Signature
    Example: eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...
    JWT Flow
            Client → Login → Server validates → Generates JWT
            Client → Sends JWT in header
            Server → Validates JWT → Allows access
    Header: Authorization: Bearer <token>
    JWT Components
      Header → Algorithm
      Payload → User data (claims)
      Signature → Security
    JWT Implementation in Spring Security
      1. Add Dependency
          <dependency>
            <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
            <artifactId>jjwt</artifactId>
          </dependency>
      2. Create JWT Utility
            public String generateToken(String username) {
                return Jwts.builder()
                    .setSubject(username)
                    .setIssuedAt(new Date())
                    .setExpiration(new Date(System.currentTimeMillis() + 1000 * 60 * 60))
                    .signWith(SignatureAlgorithm.HS256, secret)
                    .compact();
            }
      3. Create JWT Filter
            public class JwtFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {
                protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request,
                                                HttpServletResponse response,
                                                FilterChain chain) { 
                    String header = request.getHeader("Authorization");
                    if (header != null && header.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
                        String token = header.substring(7);
                        String username = jwtUtil.extractUsername(token);
                        if (username != null) {
                            UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken auth =
                                new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(username, null, List.of());
                            SecurityContextHolder.getContext().setAuthentication(auth);
                        }
                    }
                    chain.doFilter(request, response);
                }
            }
      4. Register Filter
          http.addFilterBefore(jwtFilter, UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter.class);
     Key Points: Stateless (no session), Scalable (used in microservices) and Token expiry important

SAML Authentication (SSO):
    Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is used for Single Sign-On (SSO).
    Used in enterprise systems.
  
   SAML Flow:
    User → App (Service Provider)
        → Redirect to Identity Provider (IdP)
        → Login (Okta / Azure AD)
        → IdP sends SAML response
        → User authenticated in app
    
    Components:
        Component	                    Description
        SP (Service Provider)	        Your application
        IdP (Identity Provider)	      Auth server (Okta, Azure AD)
        Assertion	                    XML containing user info
    
    Example Providers: Okta, Azure AD and ADFS

  SAML Integration in Spring Security
      1. Add Dependency
            <dependency>
              <groupId>org.springframework.security</groupId>
              <artifactId>spring-security-saml2-service-provider</artifactId>
            </dependency>
      2. Configure application.yml
              spring:
                security:
                  saml2:
                    relyingparty:
                      registration:
                        my-saml:
                          identityprovider:
                            metadata-uri: https://idp.com/metadata
      3. Security Config
            @Bean
            SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
                http
                    .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth.anyRequest().authenticated())
                    .saml2Login();
            
                return http.build();
            }
     Key Points: XML-based, Used in enterprise SSO and More secure but complex than JWT

