AuthenticationManager vs AuthenticationProvider:
AuthenticationManager:
      Main entry point for authentication
      Delegates authentication to providers
      authenticationManager.authenticate(auth);
      👉 Think of it as a controller/dispatcher
AuthenticationProvider:
      Contains actual authentication logic
      Validates credentials
      public class CustomAuthProvider implements AuthenticationProvider {
          public Authentication authenticate(Authentication auth) {
              // validate user
          }
      }
    Feature	        AuthenticationManager	        AuthenticationProvider
    Role	          Delegates	                    Executes logic
    Responsibility	Orchestration	                Validation
    Multiple?	      Uses multiple providers	      You can define many
    Flow: Request → AuthenticationManager → AuthenticationProvider → DB → Result

JWT vs Session:
JWT (Token-based):
    Stored in client (browser/mobile)
    Sent in every request
    Authorization: Bearer <token>
Session-based: 
      Stored in server memory
      Client sends session ID (cookie)

      Feature	                  JWT	                      Session
      Storage	                  Client	                  Server
      Scalability	              High                  	  Low
      State	                    Stateless            	    Stateful
      Performance              	Faster (no DB lookup)    	Slower
      Security	                Needs care (token leak)	  Safer (server control)
      Real-world usage          Microservices, APIs       Traditional web apps

Stateless vs Stateful:
Stateless: Server stores nothing. Each request is independent
  Example:
      Request1 → complete  
      Request2 → independent  
      👉 Used with JWT
Stateful: Server stores session data  
  Example: Login → Session created → reused
      👉 Used with sessions
      Feature	      Stateless	          Stateful
      Memory	      No server storage	  Uses server memory
      Scaling      	Easy	              Hard
      Performance  	Better	            Limited
      Example	      JWT	                Session

Microservices Security (API Gateway + JWT):
  Problem - In microservices: Multiple services Need centralized security
  Solution: API Gateway + JWT
  Flow : Client → API Gateway → Auth Service → JWT issued
         Client → API Gateway (with JWT)
                → Validate JWT
                → Forward to microservice
Components
    1. API Gateway - Entry point (Spring Cloud Gateway)
    2. Auth Service - Generates JWT
    3. Microservices - Trust JWT (no DB call)
Example Flow:
    1. Login → Auth Service → JWT
    2. Call API → Gateway validates token
    3. Forward request → Service
Benefits: Centralized security, No session sharing needed and Scalable
Important: Validate JWT at gateway, Use HTTPS and Token expiry + refresh token

